# Scheduling Messages And Reminders

Scheduled messages and reminders are tools that enable chatbots to send messages to users at predetermined times, enhancing user engagement and interaction.

**Scheduled Messages:** These are messages set to be delivered at a specific future time. They can be one-time messages or recurring, depending on the desired frequency. For example, a chatbot might send a daily health tip every morning or a reminder for an upcoming event. OCS provides functionalities to create and manage these scheduled messages, allowing updates to existing schedules as needed. 

**Reminders:** Reminders are notifications intended to prompt users about specific tasks or events. In OCS, chatbots can set up:

* One-off Reminders: A single notification sent at a specified time in the future.

* Recurring Reminders: Notifications that repeat at regular intervals, such as daily or weekly, to remind users of ongoing tasks or habits.

These features are particularly useful for applications requiring timely user prompts, like medication reminders, meeting alerts, or regular check-ins. 

## How To Set Up Scheduled Messages

Scheduled Messages requires [reminders](https://dimagi.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/OCS/pages/2429550658/Tool+Usage) to be configured. Once the reminders have been configured, an [event](https://docs.openchatstudio.com/concepts/events/#static-events) needs to be created in order to successfully schedule messages to the user. 

### Configuring Reminders

Below are the steps to configure the weekly surveys:

1. Add tags to the prompt that are required by recurring reminders feature.  
* {current\_datetime}  
* {participant\_data}  
2. Select the Recurring reminders feature under the tools section  
   ![][image1]

### Configuring An Event

Open Chat Studio provides an [event](https://docs.openchatstudio.com/concepts/events/) system that allows you to define actions triggered by specific events within a chat session. This functionality enables you to automate responses, manage session states, and enhance user interactions effectively.

![][image2]

Once an event has been created, the next step is to configure event details such as:

* **When…:** This refers to when the event should be triggered  
* **Then…:** This refers to the action that should take place when the event is triggered  
* **Name:** This refers to the name of the event   
* **Bot’s instructions:** This refers to the specific message/s and behaviour that is required for the schedule once the event has been triggered.

  Example:

  “Send one survey question every week. Do not repeat questions that have already been asked” 

* **Every…:** This refers to the number of times the actions should be carried out   
* **Time Period:** This refers to the frequency to which the action will be carried out i.e. once a week  
* **Repetitions:** This refers to the number of times the event will be repeated  
  ![][image3]

### Monitoring Scheduled Messages

After events have been configured, they can be monitored through the “View Logs” which mainly consist of 2 sections:

* Repeat \- The number of times a scheduled message has been sent  
* Error count \- The number of times a message has failed to be sent
